<div>
<p><strong>Example 1:</strong> Convert 100 degrees Fahrenheit to Kelvin.</p=
>
<p><strong>Solution:</strong></p>
<p>To find: Temperature in Kelvin</p>
<p>T<sub>F</sub> =3D 1000 F(Given)</p>
<p>Using Fahrenheit to Kelvin formula,</p>
<p>(T)<sub>K</sub> =3D 5/9 [(T)<sub>F</sub><sub> </sub>+ 459.67]</p>
<p>Putting the value:</p>
<p>=3D 5/9(100+459.67)</p>
<p>=3D 5/9(559.67)</p>
<p>=3D 2798.35/9</p>
<p>=3D 310.93 K</p>
<p>Therefore,<b> </b>100 degree Fahrenheit =3D 310.93 K.</p>
</div>
</li>
